The GIC Report, released annually, details our five, 10 and 20-year annualised nominal return, and our rolling 20-year real rate of return. Over 20 years up to 31 March 2018, the GIC Portfolio’s annualised real rate of return was 3.4% per year. Text Reply: We disclose information on our returns over five, 10 and 20-year time periods, risk levels, and asset and geographical distributions each year in the [GIC Report](https://www.gic.com.sg/reports/).

The GIC Report, released annually, details our five, 10 and 20-year annualised nominal return, and our rolling 20-year real rate of return. Over 20 years up to 31 March 2018, the GIC Portfolio’s annualised real rate of return was 3.4% per year. The 20-year real rate of return reflects the Government’s investment mandate, requiring GIC to invest for the long term, while the five and 10-year results provide intermediate indications of ongoing performance. [Find out more](https://www.gic.com.sg/reports/)

The GIC Report, released annually, details our five, 10 and 20-year annualised nominal return, and our rolling 20-year real rate of return. Over 20 years up to 31 March 2018, the GIC Portfolio’s annualised real rate of return was 3.4% per year. The 20-year real rate of return reflects the Government’s investment mandate, requiring GIC to invest for the long term, while the five and 10-year results provide intermediate indications of ongoing performance. User Message: What is GIC's contribution to the Budget?
Intent: Purpose of Funds - Contribution to Budget
Text Reply: Singaporeans benefit from the returns of GIC, as well as of MAS and Temasek, as they supplement the annual Budget through the Net Investment Returns Contribution (NIRC). This contribution has allowed the Government to make further investments for Singapore for the long term. [Find out more](https://www.gic.com.sg/about-gic/purpose-of-funds/)

GIC is a global long-term investor with well over US$100 billion in assets under management. Our Client, the Government of Singapore, does not publish the size of assets managed by GIC. Revealing the assets under management of GIC will, taken together with the published assets of MAS and Temasek, amount to publishing the full size of Singapore’s financial reserves. User Message: What is GIC’s source of funds?
Text Reply: We manage most of the Government's financial assets, other than its deposits in the Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS) and stake in Temasek Holdings. We receive funds from the Government for long-term management, without regard to the sources, e.g. proceeds from securities issued, Government surpluses. GIC invests across a range of asset classes in both the public and private markets – including equities, fixed income, real estate and private equity. We have investments in over 40 countries worldwide. As a rule, we do not invest in Singapore. [Visit our newsroom for our latest updates](https://www.gic.com.sg/news-and-insights/)
We seek to build a portfolio comprising asset classes that generate good real returns over the long term, while adhering to the risk tolerance outlined by our Client.

The Policy Portfolio is the central component of our investment framework and accounts for the bulk of the risk and return potential of the GIC Portfolio. There are six asset classes in the Policy Portfolio: Developed Market Equities, Emerging Market Equities, Nominal Bonds and Cash, Inflation-Linked Bonds, Private Equity and Real Estate. [Find out more](https://www.gic.com.sg/investments/investment-framework/)

Established in 1981 to manage Singapore’s foreign reserves, GIC is a global long-term investor with well over US$100 billion in assets in over 40 countries worldwide. We work to secure Singapore’s financial future by investing across a range of asset classes in the public and private markets. [Find out more about GIC.](https://www.gic.com.sg/about-gic)

GIC is a place where you can excel, both as a mid-career professional or someone starting out in your career. In fact, our GIC Internship Programme, GIC Scholarship Programme and GIC Professionals Programme will impart comprehensive learning, hands-on experience and mentoring to groom you for your preferred role. If you’re armed with drive, passion, commitment and seek growth, explore your opportunities at https://careers.gic.com.sg/.

GIC invests across a range of asset classes in both the public and private markets – including equities, fixed income, real estate and private equity. We have investments in over 40 countries worldwide. As a rule, we do not invest in Singapore. [Visit our newsroom for our latest updates](https://www.gic.com.sg/news-and-insights/)

The Policy Portfolio is the central component of our investment framework and accounts for the bulk of the risk and return potential of the GIC Portfolio. There are six asset classes in the Policy Portfolio: Developed Market Equities, Emerging Market Equities, Nominal Bonds and Cash, Inflation-Linked Bonds, Private Equity and Real Estate. [Find out more](https://www.gic.com.sg/investments/investment-framework/)
The Active Portfolio comprises skill-based strategies to add value to the Policy Portfolio, while broadly maintaining the same level of systematic risk.

Our investment framework capitalises on our core strengths including our ability to take a long-term perspective, flexible capital and sound governance structure. It has three building blocks: the Reference Portfolio, Policy Portfolio and Active Portfolio. The key to implementing our investment framework is a disciplined approach to long-term value investing. [Find out more](https://www.gic.com.sg/investments/investment-framework/)
The Active Portfolio comprises skill-based strategies to add value to the Policy Portfolio, while broadly maintaining the same level of systematic risk.
